\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the wage regression equation (true model) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\log W_{i} & = &  & \beta_{0}+\beta_{1}S_{i}+\beta_{2}A_{i}+u_{i}\\
E[u_{i}|S_{i},A_{i}] & = &  & 0
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{i}$
\end_inset

 is wage, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the years of schooling, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the ability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What we want to know is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

, the effect of the schooling on the wage 
\series bold
holding other things fixed
\series default
.
 Also called the returns from education.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An issue is that we do not often observe the ability of a person directly.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose that you omit 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 and run the following regression instead.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log W_{i}=\alpha_{0}+\alpha_{1}S_{i}+v_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}=\beta_{2}A_{i}+u_{i}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 is likely to be correlated.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The OLS estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{1}$
\end_inset

 will have the bias: 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E[\hat{\alpha}_{1}]=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}\frac{Cov(S_{i},A_{i})}{Var(S_{i})}
\]

\end_inset

- You can also say 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not consistent for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\alpha}_{1}\overset{p}{\longrightarrow}\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}\frac{Cov(S_{i},A_{i})}{Var(S_{i})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is known as 
\series bold
omitted variable bias formula
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Omitted variable bias depends on
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
