\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the dummy variables that indicate male and famale.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
male_{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & if\ male\\
0 & if\ female
\end{cases},\ female_{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & if\ female\\
0 & if\ male
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you put both male and female dummies into the regression, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}famale_{i}+\beta_{2}male_{i}+\epsilon_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $male_{i}+famale_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, we have perfect multicolinarity.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You should always omit the dummy variable of one of the groups in the linear
 regression.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For example, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}famale_{i}+\epsilon_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as the effect of being famale 
\series bold
in comparison with male
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The omitted group is the basis for the comparison.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
tightlist
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You should the same thing when you deal with multiple groups such as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}freshman_{i} & =\begin{cases}
1 & if\ freshman\\
0 & otherwise
\end{cases}\\
sophomore_{i} & =\begin{cases}
1 & if\ sophomore\\
0 & otherwise
\end{cases}\\
junior_{i} & =\begin{cases}
1 & if\ junior\\
0 & otherwise
\end{cases}\\
senior_{i} & =\begin{cases}
1 & if\ senior\\
0 & otherwise
\end{cases}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}freshman_{i}+\beta_{2}sophomore_{i}+\beta_{3}junior_{i}+\epsilon_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

